Happy Friday! As we wrap up Suicide Prevention week, we want to give you some great free resources that you can use or refer others to. The number for the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline is:
1-800-273-TALK, that‚Äôs 1-800-273- 8255. You can also text IN to 741741. An awesome app to check out is ‚ÄúA Friend Asks.‚Äù We know that COVID-19 has caused lots of changes, cancellations, and chaos these last several months. We want you to know that you aren‚Äôt alone, and that all of us involved at CPCSC care about you. We hope you have a great rest of your Friday!

post_text: Good Morning! Yesterday for Suicide Prevention week we talked about reaching out to a trusted adult if a friend needed help- BUT who do you go to if YOU are feeling upset or need help? It may be the same adult that you thought of yesterday, or it may be a different adult, teacher, coach, parent, or family friend. We know asking for help- especially for yourself- can be difficult. But the people who care about you WANT you to reach out. They WANT to be there for you during the difficult days and difficult moments. Take some time today to figure out who that trusted adult is in your life and don‚Äôt be afraid to ask for help when you need it.

post_text: Good Morning! Reminder that this is Suicide Prevention week. Today, CPCSC wants you to think about this: If a friend needed help, do you have a trusted adult that you could tell? Maybe a parent, a teacher, a coach, a neighbor, a family friend? Think about who that trusted adult is and make sure you know how to get in contact with them, without having to ask someone else. Having that info now, BEFORE a problem happens, makes reaching out easier in the moment. Sometimes our friends are struggling with problems that need the help of that trusted adult. Asking an adult for help is NOT breaking your friend‚Äôs trust- it‚Äôs making sure they stay safe and get the help they need.

post_text: Good Morning! This week is Suicide Prevention Week. CPCSC will be sharing announcements each morning to bring awareness and important information that we hope you find helpful. Today, we want to remind you about the power of checking in on your friends and others you care about. A simple text or even just ‚ÄúHow are you?‚Äù can really brighten up someone‚Äôs day! It feels good to know that others care. CPCSC challenges you to reach out to someone today and ask them how they are doing or how their day is going. We all have the ability to be a good friend who cares and is connected to others.

Thank you for your continued patience and support!

post_text: There was a "lock-out" at CPMS and Grassy Creek earlier this afternoon for about an hour. This was done because we were informed of police activity near those schools. The "lock-out" has since been lifted, and everything is back to normal. A "lock-out" is a precautionary procedure where no one is allowed in or out of our facility. Normal activities occur inside the building during these times. Sometimes we have need to ensure that the outside world is kept out of our schools for a short time. We thank you for your cooperation in keeping our schools safe!

post_text: Clark-Pleasant Community School Corporation would like to express our sincerest condolences to the family of fallen soldier Staff Sergeant Andrew Michael St. John. Losing a member of our community is never easy, and we would like to honor his life and service to our country. Staff Sgt. St. John was an infantryman with Company B, 1st. Battalion, 151st Infantry Regiment with the Indiana National Guard. During his time in the Indiana National Guard he was deployed to Iraq and Afghanistan and received several awards and medals. Staff Sgt. St. John passed away while stationed in Ft. Hood, Texas. We would like to share our appreciation and sympathy to Staff Sgt. St. John and his family.

Battalion, 151st Infantry Regiment with the Indiana National Guard. During his time in the Indiana National Guard he was deployed to Iraq and Afghanistan and received several awards and medals. Staff Sgt. St. John passed away while stationed in Ft. Hood, Texas. We would like to share our appreciation and sympathy to Staff Sgt. St. John and his family.
